At my site we run a mail server on all our workstations -- just so that
we can catch mail directed *at* one of those machines.  But we tell the
world to send mail to "ms.uky.edu" -- which isn't a physical machine.

In the nameservers we advertise MX records for each and every machine.
And even go so far as to advertise multiple MX records, to provide backup
in case the primary mail machine is down.

It seems like a perfectly reasonable set of things to do and I'm surprised
that more sites don't do it.  I think that this sort of thing should be either
required or strongly suggested in the upcoming host requirements RFC.



(BTW .. I just noticed the name of the machine you're posting from -- "XANTHIPPE",
 that happens to the the name of a character in a medieval play that I'm learning
 at the moment ... )
